Vice President Al Gore will take his first formal step toward running for president in 2000 by forming a campaign organization.
It includes Jose Villarreal as treasurer and Donna Brazile as political director.
Gore is the leading Democratic candidate.
Jesse Jackson, who may oppose Gore for the nomination, has called him a formidable candidate.
Gore has appealed to Black congressmen to help turn out voters to return the House to Democrats.
House minority leader Dick Gephardt has endorsed Gore.
Gore trails Republicans George Bush and Elizabeth Dole in early polls.
He has raised $8.9M and has visited New Hampshire.
